SIMPLE: fling
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fling
<hw>Fling</hw> <pr>(fl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Flung</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦ucr⟧ng)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Flinging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flingen</ets>, <ets>flengen</ets>, to rush, hurl; cf. Icel.
<ets>flengia</ets> to whip, ride furiously, OSw. <ets>flenga</ets> to
strike, Sw. <ets>fl⟦aum⟧nga</ets> to romp, Dan. <ets>flenge</ets> to
slash.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cast, send, to throw from the hand; to
hurl; to dart; to emit with violence as if thrown from the hand; <as>as,
to <ex>fing</ex> a stone into the pond</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is Fate that <qex>flings</qex> the dice: and, as she
<qex>flings</qex>,⟦br⟧
Of kings makes peasants, and of peasants kings.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . like Jove, his lighting <qex>flung</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know thy generous temper well.⟦br⟧
<qex>Fling</qex> but the appearance of dishonor on it,⟦br⟧
It straight takes fire.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shed forth; to emit; to scatter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun begins to <qex>fling</qex>⟦br⟧
His flaring beams.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every beam new transient colors <qex>flings</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To throw; to hurl; to throw off or down; to
prostrate; hence, to baffle; to defeat; <as>as, to <ex>fling</ex> a
party in litigation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His horse started, <qex>flung</qex> him, and fell upon him.</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 571 --></p>

<cs><p><col><b>To fling about</b></col>, <cd>to throw on all sides; to
scatter.</cd> -- <col><b>To fling away</b></col>, <cd>to reject; to
discard.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cromwell, I charge thee, <qex>fling away</qex> ambition.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p>--<col><b>To fling down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To throw to the
ground; esp., to throw in defiance, as formerly knights cast a glove
into the arena as a challenge.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This question so <qex>flung down</qex> before the guests, . . .
⟦br⟧
Was handed over by consent of all⟦br⟧
To me who had not spoken.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To overturn; to demolish; to ruin.</cd> --
<col><b>To fling in</b></col>, <cd>to throw in; not to charge in an
account; as, in settling accounts, one party <xex>flings in</xex> a
small sum, or a few days' work.</cd> -- <col><b>To fling off</b></col>,
<cd>to baffle in the chase; to defeat of prey; also, to get rid of.</cd>
<au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>To fling open</b></col>, <cd>to throw open;
to open suddenly or with violence; as, <xex>to fling open</xex> a
door.</cd> -- <col><b>To fling out</b></col>, <cd>to utter; to speak in
an abrupt or harsh manner; as, <xex>to fling out</xex> hard words
against another.</cd> -- <col><b>To fling up</b></col>, <cd>to
relinquish; to abandon; as, <xex>to fling up</xex> a
design.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Fling</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fling
<hw>Fling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw;
to wince; to flounce; <as>as, the horse began to kick and
<ex>fling</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cast in the teeth; to utter abusive language; to
sneer; <as>as, the scold began to flout and
<ex>fling</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To throw one's self in a violent or hasty manner; to
rush or spring with violence or haste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And crop-full, out of doors he <qex>flings</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>flung</qex> closer to his breast,⟦br⟧
As sword that, after battle, <qex>flings</qex> to sheath.</q>
<rj><qau>Mrs. Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fling out</b></col>, <cd>to become ugly and
intractable; to utter sneers and insinuations.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fling</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fling
<hw>Fling</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cast from the hand; a
throw; also, a flounce; a kick; <as>as, the <ex>fling</ex> of a
horse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A severe or contemptuous remark; an expression of
sarcastic scorn; a gibe; a sarcasm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, who love to have a <qex>fling</qex>,⟦br⟧
Both at senate house and king.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of dance; <as>as, the Highland
<ex>fling</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A trifling matter; an object of contempt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>England were but a <qex>fling</qex>⟦br⟧
Save for the crooked stick and the gray goose wing.</q> <rj><qau>Old
Proverb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>a short period during which one indulges one's
wishes, whims, or desires in an unrestrained manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>a love affair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>a casual or brief attempt to accomplish
something.</def> <mark>[informal]</mark> ⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> shot.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>a period during which one tries a new activity;
<as>as, he took a <ex>fling</ex> at playing tennis</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To have one's fling</b></col>, <cd>to enjoy one's self to
the full; to have a season of dissipation.</cd> <au>J. H. Newman.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧When I was as young as you, I <xex>had my fling</xex>. I led a
life of pleasure.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>D. Jerrold.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flingdust</ent>⟦br⟧
